@Node Introduction "ScreamerII Introduction"
@keywords introduction screamerii description

@{b}<< @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} Introduction >>@{ub}

   @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} is an Amiga program for @{" LightWave 4.0 " Link "LightWave"} (and better) users who:

   · Have found LightWave's built-in @{" ScreamerNet " Link "Rendering"} controller less than adequate.
AND/OR
   · Wish to work in LightWave while the CPU(s) are rendering.
AND/OR
   · Wish to use the superior environment of their Amiga to control non-Amiga "game machines" that happen to render faster.

   @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} is a stand alone program that replaces the @{" ScreamerNet " Link "Rendering"} panel in @{" LightWave " Link "LightWave"}.

   It has many @{" Features " Link "Features & Limitations"} not found on LightWave's ScreamerNet panel.
@EndNode

@Node "Revision History" "New ScreamerII Features"
@keywords revision history new features feature

@{b}<< New @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} Features >>@{ub}

@{b}V0.84:@{ub} 28-Aug-2001
   · Fixed processing of the file named by the CPU_NAMES= option. Now, the first rendering CPU gets its name from the file instead of always being named CPU1.

@{b}V0.83:@{ub}
   · Fixed an unterminated comment in the source code which caused ScreamerII to crash when the user pressed <CTRL>C before the render tasks exited on their own.

@{b}V0.82:@{ub}
   · Added this revision history
   · Put a wrapper around the locale.library function calls to enable OS 2.04 compatibility
   · Added calls to SetProgramName()
   · NOTE: Some copies of the V0.81 archive were missing icon files
@EndNode
@Node LightWave "LightWave"
@keywords lightwave

@{b}<< LightWave >>@{ub}

LightWave is a three dimensional modelling and rendering program from NewTek incorporated. It is available for many operating systems including Amiga and LoseBlows (aka Windows).

The LightWave name is copyrighted by NewTek and the @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} program is in no way associated with NewTek or LightWave. It was developed independently.

LightWave has the ability to render the same scene on multiple CPUs or multiple instances on the same CPU. This ability is known as @{" ScreamerNet " Link "Rendering"}.

@{u}ScreamerII@{uu} has been tested with Lightwave 4.0 and 5.0. However, it should work for any version of LightWave which uses the @{" ScreamerNet 2 " Link "Rendering"} protocol.

@EndNode

@Node Rendering "Rendering on a ScreamerNet"
@keywords render rendering LWSN background environment setup

@{b}<< Rendering on a ScreamerNet >>@{ub}

The Amiga @{" LightWave " Link "LightWave"} system has something called "ScreamerNet" to render scenes on multiple CPUs at the same time. A program named LWSN.FP runs on each CPU (including one on the local machine) to perform the actual rendering. One of the machines also either uses the ScreamerNet panel built into LightWave or the @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} program to control these instances of the LWSN.FP program. With @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} controlling the instances of LWSN.FP, an Amiga user with a single CPU can background render while working in LightWave without noticeable system slowdown (when setup properly).

To background render on multiple CPUs with @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} you will need a network capable of sharing hard drive volumes. This can be accomplished with AmiTCP, ParNet, Envoy or other such software packages and is beyond the scope of this document.

@{b}It is very important to setup your @{" LightWave Projects " Link "LightWave Projects"} properly and that each CPU have enough RAM to render the frames it is assigned.@{ub}

Use the LWSN.FP program as you would normally, but instead of using the LightWave ScreamerNet panel, run the @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} program with the appropriate @{" options " Link "Options"}.

@{u}ScreamerII@{uu} uses the Screamer 2 protocol. Therefore, the LWSN.FP program must be started with it's -2 parameter.

If the LWSN.FP program is run with a task priority of -2, you should be able to continue to use your Amiga without a noticeable slow down. NOTE: USING A -2 PRIORITY WILL NOT SLOW THE RENDERING WHEN YOUR AMIGA IS IDLE (i.e. you are not using it).

If you are rendering on several machines, you may wish to use ASSIGNs on the other Amigas so that from their point of view, your LightWave scene and content directory are in the same place. This can greatly simplify matters where multiple LightWave users (which are potential rendering CPUs) share the same network.

Since your ScreamerNet rendering will probably use a similar environment each time, I recommend creating an AmigaDOS script file to setup your standard environment for each ScreamerNet CPU. For example, I use the following AmigaDOS script file on my local CPU:

   .key num,taskpri/k                     ; parameter template
   .bra {                                 ; Tell AmigaDOS to use arguments enclosed in braces
   .ket }

   .def num 1                             ; Default to ScreamerNet CPU number 1
   .def taskpri -2                        ; Default task priority is -2
                                          ; (content directory is always RayWave:CurrentProject)

   FailAt 21                              ; If we need to mount drives and they are already mounted, don't stop the script
                                          ; Mount network drives here
   FailAt 20                              ; Go back to default FailAt value

   Assign RayWave: Work:LightWave         ; Make an ASSIGN for the root of the content directory

   CD System:Graphic/NewTek/Programs      ; Change to the directory where the LWSN.FP program can be found
   ChangeTaskPri {taskpri}                ; Use the proper task priority
   LWSN.FP -2 CRAD:job{num} CRAD:ack{num} ; Startup the actual LWSN program using CRAD: for the 'command' directory


And, I use the following AmigaDOS script file on one of the non-local CPU's I frequently use for ScreamerNet rendering:

   .key num                                  ; Script parameter
   .bra {                                    ; Tell AmigaDOS to recognize script arguments enclosed in braces
   .ket }

   .def num 2                                ; Default to ScreamerNet CPU number 2
                                             ; Content directory is always RayWave:CurrentProject

   FailAt 21                                 ; If the network drives are already mounted, don't stop the script
   Mount System:                             ; Mount a network drive called System
   Mount RWork:                              ; Mount a network drive called RWork
   Mount RCRAD:                              ; Mount the command directory volume of my usual machine
   FailAt 20                                 ; go back to default FailAt value

   Assign RayWave: RWork:LightWave           ; set an ASSIGN to the root of the content directory

   CD System:Graphic/NewTek/Programs         ; Change to the directory where the LWSN.FP program can be found
   ChangeTaskPri -2                          ; Don't slow down the system
   LWSN.FP -2 RCRAD:job{num} RCRAD:ack{num}  ; Startup the actual LWSN program using the networked T: for the 'command' directory
@EndNode

@Node "Tips & Hints" "ScreamerII Tips and Hints"
@keywords hints tips clues hint tip clue

@{b}<< @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} Tips and Hints >>@{ub}

· Run the LWSN.FP program with a task priority of -2. This will allow you to background render on you Amiga without a noticeable system slow down. NOTE: USING A -2 PRIORITY WILL NOT SLOW THE RENDERING WHEN YOUR AMIGA IS IDLE (i.e. you are not using it).

· Make AmigaDOS script files that set up your standard environment on each ScreamerNet CPU.

· Use ASSIGNs on the other Amigas so that from their point of view, your LightWave scene and content directory are in the same place.

· Make a Workbench project @{" icon " Link "WorkBench Usage"} that holds your most used @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} options as Tool Types and specifies @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} as the Default Tool. Also make Worbench project icons connected to your LightWave scenes. These scene icons should have no Default Tool and should have a Tool Type that specifies the LightWave scene file that the icon represents. Icons are supplied with the @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} archive.

· Setup your @{" LightWave scenes " Link "LightWave Projects"} to reference all components (images, objects, clip maps etc.) relative to your content directory instead of actually mentioning a specific path.

· You can stop @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} by pressing <ctrl>C in it's output window.

· A brief description of each @{" CLI option and Workbench Tool Type " Link "Options"} can be obtained by first typing "ScreamerII ?" and then typing "?" in the CLI window. 

·  Put the command directory on nonvolatile media such as a hard drive. This will allow the @{" RESTART " Link "RESTART"} option to function properly should the Amiga with the @{" COMMAND_DIRECTORY " Link "COMMAND_DIRECTORY"} on it be rebooted.

@EndNode
@Node "Features & Limitations" "ScreamerII Features and Limitations"
@keywords features feature limitation limitations advantages advantage

@{b}<< @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} Features and Limitations >>@{ub}

There are many advantages to using @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} over @{" LightWave's " Link "LightWave"} built-in ScreamerNet controller. Among them are:

· Allows one to work in @{" LightWave " Link "LightWave"} while a scene @{" renders " Link "Rendering"} in the background on a single CPU
· ScreamerNet CPUs can be added and removed dynamically during the rendering without problems
· Does not wait for that annoying 'Screamer Init' time found on LightWave's ScreamerNet panel
· The estimated time of completion is displayed
· Can automatically @{" skip frames " Link "MISSING_FRAMES"} that have previously been rendered
· Optionally starts all rendering CPUs @{" simultaneously " Link "MULTI_START"} instead of sequentially
· Intelligently @{" deactivates slower CPUs early " Link "SMART_END"} to speed up overall rendering time
· Adjustable rate at which the @{" command directory " Link "COMMAND_DIRECTORY"} is scanned
· Rendering CPUs can be given @{" names " Link "CPU_NAMES"} instead of just numbers
· The rendering job can be @{" RESTARTed " Link "RESTART"} seamlessly after rebooting the controller 


Other features include:

· Useable from the WorkBench or the CLI
· All @{" options " Link "Options"} are available as CLI arguments or WorkBench Tool Types
· Supports the AmigaOS catalog system. All text can be changed - even the command line arguments and Tool Types!
· When run from the WorkBench, the @{" content directory " Link "CONTENT_DIRECTORY"} is determined intelligently
· Comsumes very little CPU time
· Pressing ? a second time at the CLI prompt gives a verbose description of each @{" CLI argument " Link "Options"}
· Compatible with LightWave 4.0 using @{" ScreamerNet " Link "Rendering"} 2 protocol
· Likely compatibility with LightWave 5.0 (using ScreamerNet 2 protocol) and other rendering platforms such as Alpha (provided they can share network drives with your Amiga)


Some known limitations are:

· You cannot set the first frame and last frame to be rendered in a scene. So, if you are not using the @{" MISSING_FRAMES " Link "MISSING_FRAMES"} option, all frames of a given scene are rendered. If a partial scene render is desired, a scene file specifying the desired first frame and last frame must be created.
· @{" All scenes " Link "SCENE_LIST"} to be rendered must use the same @{" content directory " Link "CONTENT_DIRECTORY"}
· The default for the @{" content directory " Link "CONTENT_DIRECTORY"} cannot (yet) be read from the Toaster:Programs/LightWave_Support/LW-Config file
· Scenes cannot (yet) be dynamically added or removed from the @{" scene list " Link "SCENE_LIST"}
· There is no AREXX port (yet)
@EndNode
@Node "Installation" "ScreamerII Installation"
@keywords install installation setup

@{b}<< @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} Installation >>@{ub}

Installation of @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} is simple. Just:

· Copy the executable to somewhere in your path.
· Put the documentation wherever you choose.

You may also wish to attach some of the included icons to your @{" LightWave " Link "LightWave"} scene files and/or use them to store your frequently used @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} @{" options " Link "options"}.

@EndNode

@Node "Workbench Usage" "Using ScreamerII from the Workbench"
@keywords workbench usage use icon tool types icons

@{b}<< Using @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} from the Workbench >>@{ub}

All of the @{" CLI arguments " Link "Options"} in @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} are also available as Workbench icon Tool Types. Using Workbench icons makes it easier to remember your most frequently used settings.

Multiple icons can be selected. The icons and their Tool Types are processed in the order they were selected with <shift>click.

Tool Types documented as having a Workbench Scope of "per icon" act special when an icon with the @{" SCENE= " Link "SCENE"} or @{" SCENE_LIST= " Link "SCENE_LIST"} is processed. For these icons, the value of a "per icon" Tool Type will be the last value encountered so far for that Tool Type.

The value used for Tool Types that are documented with a Workbench Scope of "global" will be the last selected icon which contains that Tool Type.

Of all the icons selected, there should only be one icon that is either the @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} tool icon or a project icon that references @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} as it's default tool.

Probably the best way to set things up would be to have a few project icons that reference @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} as their default tool and have Tool Types that represent your most used settings. Then, attach an icon to each scene file which has the tool type(s) (such as SCENE= ) which relate specifically to that scene.

See @{" CLI Arguments and Tool Types " Link "Options"} for more information about how the Tool Types are processed.
@EndNode

@Node "LightWave Projects" "Setting up LightWave Projects for ScreamerII"
@keywords lightwave projects setup

@{b}<< Setting up LightWave Projects for @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} >>@{ub}

The @{" LWSN.FP " Link "Rendering"} program may not function properly if all scene elements (including where to output the image files) are not specified relative to the @{" CONTENT_DIRECTORY " Link "CONTENT_DIRECTORY"}.

On a default Amiga LightWave installation, all scene elements are specified relative to the Toaster: logical device. However, if your Amiga network has multiple LightWave users on it, you may run into problems because the directory that is Toaster: on one Amiga is probably not the same directory that is Toaster: on another Amiga.

You may also run into trouble if you choose to put those elements of a scene that @[b}you@{ub} create on a volume other than Toaster: because all scene elements must be specified (to LightWave) relative to the content directory. This means that you must not specify a volume in any of LightWave's file requesters.

The solution I arrived at was to make an ASSIGN on each rendering CPU that points to my content directory. That way, the same logical device name can be used by all rendering CPUs even though that logical device may actually be on another CPU's hard drive. I then specify to LightWave and @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} to use this ASSIGN as the content directory. (See these @{" script files " Link "rendering"} for more information.)

You cannot render to an animation when using @{u}ScreamerII@{uu}. You must render to individual frames or alpha images that are assembled into an animation upon completion of the rendering.

@{b}IMPORTANT:@{bu} LWSN.FP will not allow you to save frames or alpha images to an absolute path. You must specify an output path that is relative to the @{" Content Directory " Link "CONTENT_DIRECTORY"}.

@EndNode

@Node "Options" "CLI Arguments and Workbench Tool Types"
@keywords cli option options workbench tool type types usage argument arguments

@{b}<< CLI Arguments and Workbench Tool Types >>@{ub}

All @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} options are available as either CLI arguments or Workbench Tool Types.

The CLI arguments are note case sensitive and many have abbreviations. For a list of CLI arguments and their abbreviations, startup @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} with:

   ScreamerII ?

For more information on the CLI arguments, press the question mark key again and press return.

The Workbench Tool Types must be UPPER CASE. There are no abbreviations for the Tool Type options. Use the long version of the CLI arguments. For more information on using Workbench Tool Types see @{" Workbench Usage " Link "Workbench Usage"}.

For Tool Types that are documented as switches, the mere presence of the switch's name in a Tool Type will activate the switch but one of the values OFF, 0, NO and FALSE must be used to deactivate the switch. For example the following Tool Types will all turn on the MULTI_START switch:
   MULTI_START=ON
   MULTI_START
   MULTI_START=
   MULTI_START=1
   MULTI_START=whatever you want

However, one of the following must be used to turn off (in this case) the MISSING_FRAMES switch:
   MISSING_FRAMES=OFF
   MISSING_FRAMES=0
   MISSING_FRAMES=FALSE
   MISSING_FRAMES=NO


@{b}You can stop @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} at any time by pressing <ctrl>C in it's output window.@{ub}

The CLI arguments and Tool Types available in @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} are:

   @{" SCAN_TIME " Link "SCAN_TIME"}      - interval between "command directory" scans
   @{" MULTI_START " Link "MULTI_START"}     - start all CPUs rendering simultaneously
   @{" LOW_CPU_NUMBER " Link "LOW_CPU_NUMBER"}  - lowest CPU number to be involved with the render
   @{" HIGH_CPU_NUMBER " Link "HIGH_CPU_NUMBER"}   - highest CPU number to be involved with the render
   @{" COMMAND_DIRECTORY " Link "COMMAND_DIRECTORY"}  - shared directory used for ScreamerNet commands
   @{" SCENE " Link "SCENE"}        - scene file to be rendered
   @{" SCENE_LIST " Link "SCENE_LIST"}    - list of scene files to be rendered
   @{" CONTENT_DIRECTORY " Link "CONTENT_DIRECTORY"}  - root directory for scenes and objects
   @{" SMART_END " Link "SMART_END"}      - stop slower CPUs early to decrease overall rendering time
   @{" CPU_NAMES " Link "CPU_NAMES"}      - give a name to each rendering CPU
   @{" MISSING_FRAMES " Link "MISSING_FRAMES"}  - only render frames that don't yet exist
   @{" RESTART " Link "RESTART"}    - restart certain rendering CPUs (after a reboot)

@EndNode

@Node "SCAN_TIME" "Interval for Scans of the Command Directory"
@keywords SCAN_TIME cli option options

@{b}<< Interval for Scans of the Command Directory >>@{ub}

CLI Argument: SCAN_TIME/K/N
CLI Shortcut: TIME/K/N
Workbench Tool Type: SCAN_TIME=
Workbench Scope: global
Default Value: 3
Unit: Seconds

While rendering, the @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} program must periodically check a directory shared by all rendering CPUs for the existence of new files. This directory is known as the @{" COMMAND_DIRECTORY " Link "COMMAND_DIRECTORY"}.

This option sets the number of seconds between each scan of the COMMAND_DIRECTORY.

If this directory is on nonvolatile media such as a hard drive (this is recommended - see @{" Tips & Hints " Link "Tips & Hints"}) you may get annoyed by the constant hard drive usage every few seconds. After all, that type of annoyance is usually only reserved for Windows users.

Higher values will cause less hard drive irritation and @{b}may@{ub} decrease render times slightly on a CPU running both @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} and LWSN.FP. However, higher values may also increase the render times on other CPUs. You may have to do some experimentation to get this number where you like it.

@EndNode

@Node "MULTI_START" "Start CPUs Rendering Simultaneously"
@keywords MULTI_START cli option options

@{b}<< Start CPUs Rendering Simultaneously >>@{ub}

CLI Argument: MULTI_START/S
CLI Shortcut: MULTI/S
Workbench Tool Type: MULTI_START=
Workbench Scope: global
Default Value: OFF
Unit: switch

Normally, @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} instructs only one CPU to load a scene at a time. This is similar (although a bit better) to how @{" LightWave's" Link "LightWave"} @{" ScreamerNet " Link "Rendering"} control panel works.

However, with this switch enabled all ScreamerNet CPUs may begin loading the scene(s) simultaneously and CPUs with faster access to a scene file (for example, on a local hard drive) may begin rendering before other CPUs have finished loading the scene file.

If you have a fast network or you don't mind all the CPUs loading the same scene file (which can cause a lot of disk activity) at the same time, you should turn on this switch.

@EndNode

@Node "LOW_CPU_NUMBER" "Lowest CPU Number"
@keywords LOW_CPU_NUMBER cli option options

@{b}<< Lowest CPU Number >>@{ub}

CLI Argument: LOW_CPU_NUMBER/K/N
CLI Shortcut: LOW/K/N
Workbench Tool Type: LOW_CPU_NUMBER=
Workbench Scope: global
Default Value: 1

Each rendering CPU must be given a unique number. (@{u}ScreamerII@{uu} allows @{" NAMES " Link "CPU_NAMES"} to also be assigned to each CPU).

This option specifies the lowest CPU number @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} will involve in the render process. Usually, the default value of 1 can be used.

By using a combination of @{" HIGH_CPU_NUMBER " Link "HIGH_CPU_NUMBER"} and LOW_CPU_NUMBER, you can specify that only a certain sub-set of the available CPUs be used in the rendering. This can be handy on a network where you might have multiple instances of @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} running.

@EndNode
@Node "HIGH_CPU_NUMBER" "Highest CPU Number"
@keywords HIGH_CPU_NUMBER cli option options

@{b}<< Highest CPU Number >>@{ub}

CLI Argument: HIGH_CPU_NUMBER/K/N
CLI Shortcut: HIGH/K/N
Workbench Tool Type: HIGH_CPU_NUMBER=
Workbench Scope: global
Default Value: 5

Each rendering CPU must be given a unique number. (@{u}ScreamerII@{uu} allows @{" NAMES " Link "CPU_NAMES"} to also be assigned to each CPU).

This option specifies the highest CPU number @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} will involve in the render process. You will usually set this option to the the highest CPU number on your @{" ScreamerNet " Link "Rendering"}.

By using a combination of HIGH_CPU_NUMBER and @{" LOW_CPU_NUMBER " Link "LOW_CPU_NUMBER"}, you can specify that only a certain sub-set of the available CPUs be used in the rendering. This can be handy on a network where you might have multiple instances of @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} running.

@EndNode

@Node "COMMAND_DIRECTORY" "The Shared 'Command Directory'"
@keywords COMMAND_DIRECTORY cli option options

@{b}<< The Shared 'Command Directory' >>@{ub}

CLI Argument: COMMAND_DIRECTORY/K
CLI Shortcut: CMD/K
Workbench Tool Type: COMMAND_DIRECTORY=
Workbench Scope: global
Default Value: (see below)

To successfully render on a @{" ScreamerNet " Link "Rendering"}, the rendering CPUs must have at least one  common directory that is shared among them. This directory is used for communication between @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} and the rendering CPUs.

This option specifies the name of the shared command directory as referenced by the CPU running @{u}ScreamerII@{uu}.

When started from the CLI, @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} uses the current working directory as the default.

When started from the @{" Workbench " Link "Workbench Usage"}, @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} uses the directory of the first selected icon as the default.

@EndNode

@Node "SCENE" "A Scene to be Rendered"
@keywords SCENE cli option options

@{b}<< A Scene to be Rendered >>@{ub}

CLI Argument: SCENE/K
Workbench Tool Type: SCENE=
Workbench Scope: per icon
Default Value: (no scene)

This option instructs @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} to render the specified @{" LightWave " Link "LightWave"} scene file.

From the CLI, only one scene file can be specified with this option (use the @{" SCENE_LIST " Link "SCENE_LIST"} option to specify more). However, when @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} is started from the Workbench, each icon selected may specify it's own scene.

@{b}IMPORTANT:@{ub} All scene file names must be relative to the @{" CONTENT_DIRECTORY " Link "CONTENT_DIRECTORY"}.

@EndNode

@Node "SCENE_LIST" "A List of Scenes to be Rendered"
@keywords SCENE SCENE_LIST cli option options

@{b}<< A List of Scenes to be Rendered >>@{ub}

CLI Argument: SCENE_LIST/K
CLI Shortcut: LIST/K
Workbench Tool Type: SCENE_LIST=
Workbench Scope: per icon
Default Value: (no scene list)

This option instructs @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} to render the @{" LightWave " Link "LightWave"} scenes mentioned on each line of the specified ASCII file.

From the CLI, only one scene list can be specified with this option. However, when @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} is started from the Workbench, each selected icon can specify another scene list.

@{b}IMPORTANT:@{ub} All scene file names in a scene list must be relative to the @{" CONTENT_DIRECTORY " Link "CONTENT_DIRECTORY"}. The scene list file name itself may be relative to the content directory but is not required to be.

@EndNode

@Node "CONTENT_DIRECTORY" "The Root Directory for all Scene Elements"
@keywords CONTENT_DIRECTORY cli option options

@{b}<< The Root Directory for all Scene Elements >>@{ub}

CLI Argument: CONTENT_DIRECTORY/K
CLI Shortcut: CONTENT/K
Workbench Tool Type: CONTENT_DIRECTORY=
Workbench Scope: global
Default Value: (see below)

In order to successfully render on a @{" ScreamerNet " Link "Rendering"}, your @{" LightWave Project " Link "LightWave Projects"} should be setup so that all scene elements (including output images) are referenced relative to the directory specified on LightWave's Options panel as the 'Content Directory'.

For best results, the 'Content Directory' you have configured in your @{" LightWave " Link "LightWave"} program should be the same directory that you specify to @{u}ScreamerII@{uu}.

From the CLI, the current working directory is used as the default for this option's value.

From the @{" Workbench " Link "Workbench Usage"}, @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} tries to determine the default value for 'Content Directory' in an intelligent manner. It will use either the directory of the first selected icon which specifies a @{" SCENE " Link "SCENE"} or @{" SCENE_LIST " Link "SCENE_LIST"} OR the parent of that directory if the icon is in a drawer named "scene" or "scenes".

@EndNode

@Node "SMART_END" "Stopping Slower CPUs Early"
@keywords SMART_END cli option options

@{b}<< Stopping Slower CPUs Early >>@{ub}

CLI Argument: SMART_END/S
CLI Shortcut: SMART/S
Workbench Tool Type: SMART_END=
Workbench Scope: global
Default Value: OFF
Unit: switch

If certain CPUs on your @{" ScreamerNet " Link "Rendering"} are @{b}much@{ub} slower than other ones, the overall rendering time can be reduced by not assigning frames near the end of the rendering session to the slower CPUs because it may take them longer to render one frame than it takes the fast CPUs to render the remaining frames.

When this switch is activated, @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} will not assign frames near the end of the render to CPUs which have render times so slow that they would not finish (on average) before the faster CPUs could render the remaining frames.

@EndNode

@Node "CPU_NAMES" "Giving Names to Rendering CPUs"
@keywords SMART_END cli option options

@{b}<< Giving Names to Rendering CPUs >>@{ub}

CLI Argument: CPU_NAMES/K
CLI Shortcut: NAMES/K
Workbench Tool Type: CPU_NAMES=
Workbench Scope: global
Default Value: (generated names)
Unit: file name

If this is option is supplied, @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} will identify the rendering CPUs by text names fetched from the specified file.

The format of the CPU_NAMES file is as follows:
   Each CPU name is specified on a line by itself.
   The first line in the file will correspond to CPU number 1, the second line will correspond to CPU number 2 and so on.

When this option is not supplied, @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} will identify the rendering CPUs by generated names which are based on the ScreamerNet CPU numbers. See @{" Rendering " Link "Rendering"} for more information about ScreamerNet CPU numbers.

@EndNode

@Node "MISSING_FRAMES" "Rendering Only Non-Rendered Frames"
@keywords MISSING_FRAMES cli option options workbench

@{b}<< Rendering Only Non-Rendered Frames >>@{ub}

CLI Argument: MISSING_FRAMES/S
CLI Shortcut: MISSING/S
Workbench Tool Type: MISSING_FRAMES=
Workbench Scope: per icon
Default Value: OFF
Unit: switch

When this switch is on, @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} will scan the frames rendered so far and instruct the @{" LWSN.FP " Link "Rendering"} programs to only render those frames which do not presently have output frame files associated with them.

Sometimes, the frames rendered at @{u}ScreamerII@{uu}'s startup will not be sequential. This can happen if your @{" ScreamerNet " Link "Rendering"} rendering has been interrupted or for other reasons. Instead of making several @{" SCENE " Link "SCENE"} files that reference each non-sequential frame that needs to be rendered, it is easier to turn on this switch.

@EndNode

@Node "RESTART" "Restarting CPUs when ScreamerII Starts"
@keywords RESTART cli option options workbench

@{b}<< Restarting CPUs when @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} Starts >>@{ub}

CLI Argument: RESTART/M
CLI Shortcut: RESTART/M
Workbench Tool Type: RESTART=
Workbench Scope: global
Default Value: (no CPUs restarted)
Unit: CPU numbers

It is always OK to stop and restart a CPU running @{" LWSN.FP " Link "Rendering"} (as long as @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} continues to run) because @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} will automatically re-issue the aborted frame to a rendering CPU when it re-starts.

Similarly, it is OK to stop and restart @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} (with the same @{" SCENES " Link "SCENE"} and @{" SCENE_LISTS " Link "SCENE_LIST"}) because it will automatically detect the scene and frame that were last issued to the rendering CPUs and resume where the process was interrupted.

However, if you reboot the rendering CPU which is also running @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} and then re-start @{u}ScreamerII@{uu}, it may erroneously assume that the rendering CPU which was rebooted is still working on the last frame it was issued. It is for this reason that the RESTART option exists.

The RESTART option is normally used only when the @{" COMMAND_DIRECTORY " Link "COMMAND_DIRECTORY"} is stored on non-volatile media (which is recommended in @{" Tips & Hints " Link "Tips & Hints"}). If this is not the case, all rendering CPUs will have to be manually re-started when the CPU holding the content directory is rebooted.

The CPUs mentioned (by number) in the RESTART value will always be re-started by @{u}ScreamerII@{uu} regardless of what scene and frame it thinks the CPU is working on.

As indicated by the /M above, multiple CPU numbers may be specified and this option must appear at the end of the CLI  command. Separate the CPU numbers by spaces. The keyword "ALL" (without the quotes) may be used to re-start every rendering CPU.

@EndNode

@Node "Registration" "ScreamerII Registration"
